			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Since the author of this essay claims to be a &quot;non-casual&quot; player who is able to devote 8 hours a day to the game, and I would put myself in the category of a &quot;casual&quot; player, I'd like to add my own opinion...<BR>
<BR>
I have only been playing EQ for about 4 months now.  I have a 25th level Ranger that is my Main, and a 16th level Shadow Knight that is quickly becoming my &quot;new Main&quot;.  I am married, with a 4 year old daugher, and generally get to devote about 2 to 3 hours, three or four nights a week on the game.  Weekends I usually find time to get at least a good 6 or 8 hour session in.<BR>
<BR>
Since my characters are nowhere near the level that this topic addresses, I've yet to experience the challenge of taking on an Uber mob.  But I have made friends of that level, and I've joined a guild.  All the folks I've talked to have explained to me that Mobs of the nature that are being discussed here take huge numbers of characters to take them down.  Even at 60th level, it would take more than just a normal group of six players to defeat these Mobs.  It takes entire guilds of 60th level characters to face these Mobs.<BR>
<BR>
So why do I get the feeling that the author of this essay expects casual players to log on at their leisure and have the ability to wander into one of these Uber zones, send out a LFG shout, find a few other players, and then proceede to take on one of these spawns?  It sounds to me like attacking one of these Uber Mobs takes planning, coordination, and TIME - basically the kind of dedication that goes beyond casually logging on for a few hours and finding a group to camp with for a while.<BR>
<BR>
I continually read posts where players who run into difficulties in the game want the game changed to make things easier for them.  Adding more Uber Mobs or changing spawn times simply to make things easier for a certian demographic of players is ridiculous.  Casual player or not, if you want to acheive something more difficult in the game, don't ask Verant to make it easier for you - you should just work harder.<BR>
<BR>
Example:  As a Ranger, I wanted to make a Trueshot Bow.  The most important part of the bow is Micro Servos in Steamfront.  At the normal times that I play the game during the week, there were often a lot of Rangers camping the zone looking for this very same item.  So did I whine to Verant and ask that they make Micro Servos a more common drop?  No.  I waited until the weekend, set my alarm for 2:00am and got up when the zone was less crowded, farmed my Micro Servos, went back to bed and slept in on Sunday.<BR>
<BR>
I have digressed too far... but my original point was this:  The whole concept of Everquest is that there are challenges in the game that you must overcome.  From 1st level to 60th, the game never hands you anything on a silver platter - you have to fight (literally) for it.  So why do you suddenly want 60th level Mobs served up for you to kill at your leisure?  If you want to take down these Uber Spawns, join a guild, set some time aside, and particiapte in a Raid.  That's the way the game intended it to be.<BR>
<BR>
... 2cp worth from an addicted &quot;casual&quot; player ... for what it's worth? =P<BR>
<BR>
Buchalter Iceraven &lt;Heroes of Destined Heights&gt;<BR>
26th level Ranger  - Vazaelle<BR>
<BR>
Gumgrak<BR>
16th level Shadow Knight - Vazaelle
				</font>
