	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				 It's pretty easy for one side or another to trash the other with comments like<BR>
 &quot;lazy&quot;, &quot;communist&quot;, &quot;lifeless&quot;, etc., but there are some valid points to be <BR>
made here.<BR>
<BR>
 A 'casual' player who grinds away at it WILL eventually hit 60. And WILL be able<BR>
to work on his AA points. And WILL be stuck, even if uberguilds don't have time<BR>
requirements. This is because in the uberguilds, loot is divided based on the<BR>
'points' system. Therefore, those who can't participate at a high percentage of<BR>
guild events don't get loot. Just that plain and simple.<BR>
<BR>
 A 'casual' player is not one who has not 'worked' for his level/equipment, etc.<BR>
Now, some people who devote more time to things like working on tradeskilling/<BR>
exploring/questing aren't grinding as hard as a 'hard-core' player, but those<BR>
who hit 60 had to kill just as many mobs and put their avatars on the line and<BR>
learn their job, regardless of /time played. Unless they're like the 52 BL on Brell<BR>
who was the result of a bet between two uberguilds. But to say that because they<BR>
took more than, say, 60 days/played or some other ridiculous figure to reach<BR>
that peak, that they're not worthy of SOME reward for their effort? Rubbish.<BR>
<BR>
 Now, the 'casual' argument about 8 hour players is somewhat valid, but the<BR>
statements about less value per hour of 'hardcore' gaming is bunk. What you're<BR>
essentially paying for is x number of hours per month per server. Instead of the<BR>
faulty logic of dividing your payment by your hours played, use the correct figure<BR>
of the number of hours the server is up. Remember, the server is up whether or<BR>
not you're there, and since you're not paying on a time schedule like a phone<BR>
call and since Sony/Verant can't anticipate what hours you'll be on, you're just<BR>
paying an equal share per hour the server is up as any other player, whatever<BR>
their habits.<BR>
<BR>
 The complaints are valid: A better way to run this railroad would be to key<BR>
encounters so that multiple raids AT THE SAME TIME could hit the same mobs.<BR>
Compartmentalize each raid on it's own seperate plane. At the same time,<BR>
adjust drop rates so that equipment would keep its rarity. This would alleviate<BR>
the rarity of the mobs while keeping the rarity of epics and planar loot, as it's<BR>
doubtful even at full maturity a server will support more than two raids in one <BR>
zone at any one specific time.<BR>
<BR>
 Mil Mascaras<BR>
 Casual gamer climbing<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
