			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				     There are a few simple truths that are being overlooked by the writer of the original post.  The very high level creatures which you think are not fairly being shared by the high level guilds, in fact REQUIRE multiple high level groups to take down.  The &quot;casual&quot; player you speak of will have a hard time collecting enough friends to actually get to,  and kill these mobs during their small ammount of play time.  That is where uber guilds come in.  They are not evil corporations bent on taking over the economy, or any other such thing.  They are merely players,  both casual and evercrack addicts that have banded together for a common cause.  Fun.  taking down a king of an evil race, or a dragon,  or an avatar is just as much fun for the person who spends 12 hours a day playing as it is for the person who spends 2 hours a day playing.  There is no reason to penalize a player because of the ammount of time that person plays per day weather a little or a lot. You blame people for spending alot of time playing their favoritte game.  That is unfair on your part.  If you log on and find that the mob you hoped to camp is already taken,  go find something else to do.  Verant does not need to create more dragons to throw into Zones like Gore, so that they can kill the lower level players just so that YOU can have your dragon whenever you want it. (I often see Gore, Woushi, Rolandal, ect up anyway so obviously more dragons is not a solution)<BR>
     Casual players that have reached lv.60 (the reason for this whole discussion) have just as much chance of getting into an &quot;uber&quot; guild as people who play only a few hours a week,  so saying that uber guilds are all teenage asians that sit around waiting for patch day to come so they can take all the monsters before any &quot;casual&quot; level 60 characters can get them is obscene and silly,  and I personally find it rather insulting to the players that have poured their heart and souls into a character so that they could join a legendary guild and take on these beasts and gods that they have been hearing about since being a little tyke.  So what if it took you two years longer than it did for me?  my play time may have been more concentrated,  but does that make my time trivial?  I think not.  Does that grant you special rights or privelages just because you spent a year longer getting to the point I am at?  I think not.  High road,  or low road,  the destination is the same.  <BR>
     Many players play during the hours that the patches normally take place.  I am one of those players.  I also believe many of these Teenage Asians you speak of are also players who play during the wee hours just as I do.  the rush to get to the good mobs isnt a rush to beat the &quot;casual&quot; players,  but simply a rush to get to the mob you've been waiting all those patching hours to camp,  and just because there was a patch does not mean that that mob will pop any faster,  it just resets the delay timers and spawns the mob more random for the first pop, giving a better CHANCE of getting the mob.<BR>
     A guild effort to get a Beastlord to lv.60 is a completely seperate topic.  If a guild wishes to make a concerted effort to level up a new class to lv.60,  I say bravo and give a brownie point for team effort.  Because that is what it would take.       <BR>
     In closing,  my suggestion to you &quot;casual&quot; players out there that feel it is unfair that you are lv.60,  but do not get to kill Lady Vox during the 2 hours you play during a day is this.  Join an uber guild to take on Uber mobs.  No guilds,  uber or not, have a time per week requirement to join.  The game is designed to have fun with others online.  that is why we play on a server with 2000 other people instead of a diablo game with 4 people.  Join a guild that is worthy of your status in the game,  because yes,  you are Level 60,  Yes you are Uber,  and yes you should be killing dragons ect.  If you choose to not join up with a group of players that is capable of taking down these mobs then do not moan about not being in on the fun stuff.  Get off your duff and take some initiative.  If you are LV60,  I guarentee you will not have trouble finding a guild that goes dragon raiding from time to time.  Most guilds schedule such things well in advance to make it easier for their &quot;casual&quot; members to make arrangements to go.<BR>
<BR>
*Tosses two copper on the ground and walks away*<BR>

